# =F0=9F=A5=82 Tipsy Tip

### Compose Shared Element Debugging Just Got a Lot Less Painful

If you've ever tried to debug a shared element transition in Compose and en=
ded up staring at your screen like =F0=9F=A7=8D wondering why your hero ani=
mation is doing something deeply cursed =E2=80=94 good news. The Compose te=
am heard you.

In **Compose 1.11.0-alpha03**, a new composable called `LookaheadAnimationV=
isualDebugging` was quietly added, and it's exactly what it sounds like: a =
debug wrapper that adds visual cues to your shared element transitions so y=
ou can actually _see_ what's happening under the hood.

The usage is beautifully simple. When you're debugging, just wrap your `Sha=
redTransitionLayout` in it:

```
LookaheadAnimationVisualDebugging {
    SharedTransitionLayout {
        // your shared element transition content
    }
}
```
This is an alpha API, so treat it as a debugging tool only =E2=80=94 don't =
ship it to production. But for development? This is the kind of quality-of-=
life addition that saves you from hours of `Log.d` archaeology trying to fi=
gure out why your transition is snapping instead of animating smoothly.

Shared element transitions are one of those Compose features that look magi=
cal when they work and absolutely maddening when they don't. The problem ha=
s always been that the lookahead layout system =E2=80=94 which powers the t=
ransitions =E2=80=94 operates in a way that's hard to observe from the outs=
ide. You'd see the end result but have no visibility into the intermediate =
states.

`LookaheadAnimationVisualDebugging` changes that by surfacing visual overla=
ys that let you track the lookahead bounds, the actual bounds, and how they=
're animating relative to each other. It's the kind of tool that makes you =
go "why didn't this exist from day one?" =F0=9F=98=85

View image: (https://media.beehiiv.com/cdn-cgi/image/fit=3Dscale-down,forma=
t=3Dauto,onerror=3Dredirect,quality=3D80/uploads/asset/file/401b5d7b-66b6-4=
c0f-8747-9b1b999de601/26-shared.png?t=3D1774711821)
